[0.004, "o", "\u001b[2;58H\u001b[0m\u001b[1;1H\u001b[38;5;130m  1\u001b[0m\u001b[1C+++                                  \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m  2\u001b[0m\u001b[1Ctitle = 'Announcing gh-observer: Because Waiting for \u001b[103mCI\u001b[0m Should Not Be a Mystery'\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m  3\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cdate = 2026-03-08T02:00:00-00:00\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m  4\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cdraft = false\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m  5\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cdescription = 'I Got Tired of Watching \u001b[35m`\u001b[0mgh pr checks --watch\u001b[35m`\u001b[0m Fail Me, So I Built Something Better'\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m  6\u001b[0m\u001b[1Ccover.image = '/posts/2026-FIX.png'\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m  7\u001b[0m\u001b[1Ccover.hidden = false       \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m  8\u001b[0m\u001b[1Ckeywords = [\"github-actions\", \"github-cli-extension\"]\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m  9\u001b[0m\u001b[1Ctags = [\"github\", \"programming\"]\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 10\u001b[0m\u001b[1CShowToc = true \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 11\u001b[0m\u001b[1C+++\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 12\r\n 13\u001b[0m\u001b[1CLook, I know what you're thinking: \"Another dev scratched their own itch and\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 14\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cnow they want to tell me about it.\" Guilty. But hear me out, because this\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 15\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cparticular itch has probably been annoying you too, and the scrat"]
[0.000, "o", "ch is        \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 16\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cgenuinely useful.                                                           \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 17\u001b[0m\u001b[1C                                                                        \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 18\u001b[0m\u001b[1C\u001b[35m## \u001b[0m\u001b[35mThe Problem Nobody Talks About\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 19\r\n 20\u001b[0m\u001b[1CHere's the scenario that broke me: I push a PR, immediately run \u001b[35m`\u001b[0mgh pr checks\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 21\u001b[0m\u001b[1C--watch\u001b[35m`\u001b[0m, and... it bombs out with an error because GitHub Actions hasn't   \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 22\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cqueued anything yet. So I wait. I run it again. Maybe it works, maybe it      \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 23\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cdoesn't. And when it finally does start showing me checks, I'm staring at a \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 24\u001b[0m\u001b[1Clist of job names with no idea whether that \u001b[35m`\u001b[0m3m 52s\u001b[35m`\u001b[0m I've been waiting is\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 25\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cnormal or a sign that something's silently wedged.\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 26\u001b[0m\u001b[1C                                                                               \r\n"]
[0.002, "o", "\u001b[38;5;130m 27\u001b[0m\u001b[1CThe standard \u001b[35m`\u001b[0mgh pr checks --watch\u001b[35m`\u001b[0m has had some real gaps for a while now:   \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 28\u001b[0m\u001b[1C                                                                     \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 29 -\u001b[0m \u001b[1m**It doesn't handle startup delay.**\u001b[0m GitHub Actions typically takes 30-90\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 30\u001b[0m\u001b[1C  seconds to queue jobs after a PR is created or pushed to. The built-in\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 31\u001b[0m\u001b[3Cwatcher just... gives up during that window.\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 32 -\u001b[0m \u001b[1m**No queue latency.**\u001b[0m You can see a job is \"in progress,\" but you have no\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 33\u001b[0m\u001b[1C  idea if it's been sitting in a queue for 2 seconds or 45 seconds before it\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 34\u001b[0m\u001b[1C  started.                                                                    \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 35 -\u001b[0m \u001b[1m**No runtime metrics.**\u001b[0m Is that job that's been \"running\" for a while\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 36\u001b[0m\u001b[3Cactually running, or has GitHub just not updated the status yet? Who knows!\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 37\u001b[0m\u001b[1C                "]
[0.000, "o", "                                                               \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 38\u001b[0m\u001b[1CSo naturally, I did what any reasonable developer does when something annoys\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 39\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cthem enough: I spent way more time building a solution than I would have lost\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 40\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cjust dealing with the annoyance. Classic.\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 41\u001b[0m\u001b[1C   \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 42\u001b[0m\u001b[1C\u001b[35m## \u001b[0m\u001b[35mIntroducing gh-observer\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 43\u001b[0m\u001b[1C                                                                             \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 44\u001b[0m\u001b[1C\u001b[35m`\u001b[0mgh-observer\u001b[35m`\u001b[0m is a GitHub CLI extension that replaces \u001b[35m`\u001b[0mgh pr checks --watch\u001b[35m`\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 45\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cwith something that actually tells you what's going on. It's a full TUI\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 46\u001b[0m\u001b[1C(terminal UI) that polls GitHub's API every 5 seconds and shows you the\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 47\u001b[0m\u001b[1Cinformation you actually care about.\r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 48\u001b[0m\u001b[1C                                                                           \r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[38;5;130m 49\u001b[0m\u001b[1CHere's what a typical run looks like:                                       \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 50\u001b[0m\u001b[3C                                                                          \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 51\u001b[0m\u001b[1C\u001b[35m```ShellOutput\u001b[0m                                                     \r\n\u001b[38;5;130m 52\u001b[0m\u001b[1CPR #5: 🔶\u001b[52;14H [claude] /init 21:04:15 UTC     \u001b[53;105H2,54\u001b[10CTop\u001b[53;105H\u001b[K\u001b[53;105H2,54\u001b[10CTop\u001b[2;58H\u001b[34h\u001b[?25h"]
